review_blob: Deep black/brown, abundant tan head with alarmingly large bubbles. Aroma of roasted malt. Flavor of dark chocolate, coffee. A little grassy hops. Full-bodied. Really nice stuff.

Gold, diminishing offwhite head. No aroma to speak of. Malty. Where are the hops? Caramel, some oxidisation. I dont know if I got a bad bottle or what. Reasonably full-bodied for a lager but direly lacking in all other respects. Perhaps Count Grischnackh killed Euronymous because the latter gave him a bottle of this. Who knows?

Looks good, but is a boring watery waste of time and money.  And I could get two 40-ounce bottles of Haffenreffer Private Stock for the price of this. If it is in fact retired, I applaud the brewers for that decision.
Free sample, from a little plastic cup outside the good beer store in Emmaus. Fairly standard yellow lager, boring.

Gold, diminishing creamy white head. Smells a lot like bourbon, although with some yeast notes. Tasted a lot like bourbon cut with seltzer. Not bad, but still kind of disappointing; if I didnt like bourbon this would get a very bad rating indeed.

Erm... It was on discount, and I felt that I hadnt had enough swill lately. Imagine that you have some regular Bud and some cheap berry-flavored sparkling water. Combine them. This will give you some idea of the aroma, appearance, flavor, and palate. Theres no discernible flavor from the ginseng or guarana, which is a shame because either one might actually taste fairly interesting in a well-made brew. The caffeine did keep me up; I spent most of last night sitting around listening alternately to James Brown, May Blitz, and the Trojan Records Roots boxed set before eventually settling down to bizarre dreams about the Chinese New Year in Trinidad.

Brownish-red, big beige head. Aroma sour, fruity, funky. Flavor sour, fruity (cherries, plums, pomegranate,) funky, some oak. This is one where I dont miss hops; enough is going on without them. Not full-bodied in a way that would involve heaviness, but thanks to the sourness it fills the mouth in a really nice way. Im reminded again of why I became a beer geek.
Cloudy gold, foamy white head. Yeasty-sour aroma. malt, hops, yeast, almost a hefeweizen-like flavor. Light, spritzy, kind of boring.

Opaque brownish black beer, with humongous dense light-tan head like the froth on a good espresso except, as I said, humongous.Aroma of yeast, dried fruit, some slight alcohol, and an inexplicable woodiness. Flavor is full of dried fruit and some chocolate, with a typical Belgian yeast funk and grassy hops that contribute little bitterness. I taste suprisingly little roast or alcohol. Voluptuously full-bodied. By far the best beer Ive had in a while.

Opaque brown, enormous long-lasting beige head. Very visibly flocculent yeast. Smells vaguely of barbecue. Flavor spicy, vinous, smoky. Hops buried under the smoke. Medium to light body. Very good, overall, but not an everyday beer by any means.

Dark brown/black with reddish glints and a diminishing tan head. Dried fruit and malt aroma. Malt, chocolate, raisins. Maybe some peat, but maybe thats just me thinking "Hey! Scottish!" Oddly light-bodied for the style, kind of spritzy in a way that would probably be annoying if I was drinking it chilled. Good thing Im not, eh? Finishes with grassy, oolong-like hops. Quite pleasing.
The color of rosewood, dense offwhite head. Aroma of malt and yeast. Malt, caramel, a little roast, subtle grassy-bitter hops. Dry finish with a vague sourness that isnt at all bad.

Pale gold. I cant say much about the head because Im drinking this the traditional way (bottle sheathed in a paper bag) but there is a ring of foam around the edge. Aroma of adjuncts. Flavor surprisingly malty, but with some adjuncts in the background. I cant taste any alcohol or hops. Thin body, quite spritzy. Fairly inoffensive, although this does make it pretty much characterless.
beer_name: St. Ides High Gravity Malt Liquor

review_blob: Bottled. Deep red-brown, scanty head. Aroma sherrylike, yeast. Flavor of fruit: apples, cherries, raisins. Some sherrylike notes, particularly in the finish. Not a big hop presence, but the flavor was balanced so that wasnt missed. Very rich velvety mouthfeel.

Gold, with big offwhite head. Aroma of hops, gee whiz; pine, citrus, ganja, newly mown hay (Phosgene! On with your gas masks!.)  Flavor of hops, with grass clippings replacing the hay/phosgene and a bit of malt, otherwise still pine, citrus, and ganja. Medium-light body. Oddly not all that bitter, although because of the alcohol content Im drinking it at room temp. Colder it would probably be far more bitter. The alcohol is extremely well hidden.

Amber, with little white floaties and fluffy white head. Aroma of yeast, bubblegum, spices, much like a hefeweizen. Tastes very hefe-like, too, yeasty/clovey and phenolic flavors over a malt core. Theres an elusive sourness reminiscent of Schinkenbrot sneaking around in the background that keeps this from getting boring and makes me significantly less irritated about the paucity of hops. Light-bodied. I think it might be better with Middle Eastern or Greek food than Italian, but as I do not have immediate access to shawarma or dolmades, this will have to be determined on a future occasion.

Orange, dense tan head. Yeasty aroma. Malty, bready, some dried fruit. I do get some nuttiness; I never would have thought of that without BennyTicklez mentioning it. Reasonable bitterness. Medium/light bodied. Not too bad, especially for the price.

Dark cloudy brown with orange edges and a tan rocky head. Aroma of yeast, spice, dried fruit. Flavor of dried fruit, dark chocolate, some smoke. Alcohol hidden extremely well, but theres nonetheless a warming characteristic to this. Medium body. Excellent all around, and extra appearance points for having a gnome in a kilt on the label.
Reddish brown, tan head. Yeasty/spicy aroma. Some roastiness, herbal hops, slight sourness, bitter finish. Medium-light body. Not bad but not great.
Cloudy. Coconut, alcohol, koji funk. Very sweet, slightly thicker than most sake. Kind of disappointing.
beer_name: Sho Chiku Bai (Pine Bamboo Plum) Nigori Sake

review_blob: Black with reddish glints, tan head. Aroma faintly oceanic. Oddly light-bodied, with roastiness, chocolate, and a slight saltiness.

Amber, offwhite head. Aroma sort of, well, generally beery, nothing in particular stands out. Reminiscent of Yuengling Traditional, but kind of sweeter and with a little more hop bitterness. Medium body. Pretty decent but not earth-shattering. And Luxembourg is cool...

Dark brown beer, creamy beige head. Smells Belgian, bready/spicy. Surprisingly light body, chocolaty malt and spicy, woody/herbal hops. Theres a little bit of dried fruit flavor. I kind of agree with TChrome about this being like Stone 8, except that I like this one more...
beer_name: HeBrew Miraculous Jewbelation Eighth Anniversary Ale

review_blob: Deep amber, dense persistent beige head. Aroma of hops, alcohol, vanilla. Full body. Tastes like chocolate, dried fruit, vanilla. Some hoppiness. Very bourbony. Yogi_Beeras right about the celery; both my girlfriend and I taste it. Very well done, I think I like this more than regular Blithering Idiot.
UPDATED: DEC 3, 2004

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Red/amber, dense offwhite head. Aroma of malt, some smokiness. Not very aggressively smoky. Medium body. Flavor of malt, dried fruit, some herbal/spicy stuff going on. Not much discernible in the hop department, but really nice anyway. My girlfriend, who doesnt normally like beer, liked this. I like it too, and so did her rats...
Black, diminishing tan head. Malty, some toastiness. Medium body. I cant taste any hops. Not awful, but nowhere near great.
Amber, offwhite head. Malty, caramel-like in aroma and flavor. Some grassy hoppiness in the finish, but not too bitter. Good stuff.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Cloudy amber, big off-white head. Yeasty, spicy aroma; coriander rather than cloves. Flavor much like the aroma. Very slight grassy bitterness. Fairly light body.

Looks like a typical lager. Sweetish, malty. Very slight grassy hops. Light body, but not too light. Practically Dortmundery, what with the 6% and all. Not unpleasant as this sort of thing goes, and now I can use my little 1/4-liter German stoneware mug...
Reddish amber, small beige head. Aroma of malt. Hugely malty flavor, caramel and roastiness. Not much hop presence. Full body.

Deep brownish black, with a rapidly diminishing dark tan head. Aroma of bourbon. Flavor evocative of some kind of dessert involving coffee, chocolate, and bourbon, with some interesting shifts in the balance as it warms. Some vinous (sour mash?) notes on the finish. Full-bodied. The oakiness is nice; this is definitely something I like a lot.

Deep opaque brownish black, diminishing tan head. Aroma kind of like German whole-grain bread. Very sweet, chocolaty, bready flavor. Light-medium body. Some bitterness which I think is from the roasted malt; theres really nothing noticable as far as hops go. I like it, although it could use a tad more body.

Cloudy amber with a great many floaties, thick but diminishing head. Aroma of citrussy hops. Tastes amazingly hoppy, kind of like grapefruit and Dragonwell green tea simultaneously. Theres not really any kind of discernible malt, although this has nice body. Its quite satisfying, though; the hops are so skillfully handled that the malt isnt missed. Excellent beer.

Very pale yellow, kind of hazy. Big dense white head. (Yeah, I know youre supposed to drink this kind of thing from a bottle sheathed in a paper bag, but hey, Im a weirdo.) Aroma faint, slight grassy hops. Very sweet, light-bodied, kind of boring. Maybe with the ale yeast and all this would be better if not quite so cold.

On tap; I want to try this out of the bottle. Dark amber, nitro head too dense to let any aroma through. Malty. Some hops when it warms up. Nitro mouthfeel obscures how full or light it might really be. Good, though, for nitro.

Deep amber, dense offwhite head. Aroma of citrusy hops, dried fruit, alcohol. Very woody flavor; toasty, fruity, bitter. None of the ganja notes that I get from the 60 Minute. Medium to full body. Very tasty indeed, but then Ive been known to chew hop pellets. Sometime soon I need to get my hands on a bottle of the 120 Minute...

Boooooooooooring. Yellow, rapidly diminishing head, metal aroma, mild sweet flavor, slight hops. Vaguely reminiscent of Red Stripe. When will I learn that just because a label in Cyrillic looks cool it doesnt mean that I should buy the beer?
Pale gold, big foamy white head. Metallic hop aroma.Medium body, very little flavor.

Brown, with a slight orangey tinge and a beige head. Cloudy, because I poured it quicker than I should have poured a bottle-conditioned beer. Faint malty/bready aroma. Malt, nuttiness, toastiness, some dried fruit. Nice subtle hop bitterness and leafy flavor. The level of carbonation is actually quite nice; refreshing but not schpritzy. On the full side of medium-bodied. 

I just noticed this: Holy hell, that's a lot of yeast in the bottle, even for something bottle-conditioned. There's almost as much at the bottom of my glass.

Looks like any mass-produced lager. Aroma kind of bready but faint, some alcohol. Fairly inoffensive fruity/malty flavor, adjuncts, no hops whatsoever. Oh, wait, theres a hint of grassiness.
Not particularly offensive, yet not particularly good.

Rosewood color, beige head.Very bready aroma, some caramel, a hint of hops. Flavor toasty, woody. Some dried fruit and alcohol. Im not sure whether its complex or cluttered. Fairly quick finish, some bitterness. Oddly light-bodied. Kind of rough around the edges; it might well benefit from aging. I know this is supposed to be good, and Ive really liked the other Stone products Ive had, but this just isnt doing it for me tonight. Maybe if I hadnt just had 750ml of Cuvee Renee Id like it more, though.

Cloudy amber, diminishing beige head. Aroma of yeast and lactic acid sourness. Flavor of caramel, some fruit, grass, and a good share of sourness. A light roastiness somehow comes through, slight shades of hojicha. Medium-bodied. I like it.

Dark brown, scant tan head. Bready aroma. Roast, fruit, wood, very slight dry bitterness. Medium body I agree with Probiere, quite portlike. This might, like port, be very good with some high-cacao chocolate. Excuse me for a moment while I get out a piece of the Lindt 85%... Oh wow. Thats a darn good combination.

Hazy amber. Dense white head that diminishes rapidly. (This is relieving after reading all the other ratings and then having trouble with the cork.) Vinous aroma. Sour, fruity/spicy. Some woodiness and a nice earthy, old-books funk as well. Slight leafy hop notes. Alcohol quite well-hidden. Is this really from England? If someone set a glass of this in front of me without telling me what it was I would instantly have said some sort of gueuze. I think this will lose appearance points for coming in a bottle that I cant use for homebrew, but I find it very pleasing.

2003, drank from my Rodenbach stem glass because my snifter is missing. Dark brown with reddish glints, initially abundant tan head. Floral aroma, some fruit, alcohol. Flavor of dark chocolate, dried cherries, Maofeng green tea, five-spice powder. The hop presence comes out in the tealike flavor; I compare it to Maofeng because that has a very fruity/grassy/spicy flavor. Deceptively drinkable because of its rather surprisingly light body. I have become a lightweight from not drinking as often as before, I probably should have found someone to split this with. Oh well, drunkenness is fun.

I got this at a little deli with take-out beer in Allentown. Served the traditional way, with the 40-oz bottle sheathed in a brown paper bag. Since this sort of thing is most often consumed this way, I see little point in doing otherwise.
Golden-yellow, a white head forms when I open the cap but it diminishes. Aroma oddly similar to Spam or canned corned beef. Medium to light-bodied. Fairly sweet, with notes of malt, Tostitos, and a little alcohol. Vague hop presence. Slightly fruity; did they use top-fermenting yeast? Theres actually an unnervingly Belgianesque quality to this, kind of like if one of the less scrupulous macros tried to imitate Duvel or Delirium Tremens. I kind of like this; I do have a soft spot in my heart for malt liquor for some reason (memories of sitting around with my friends in the back room of a beer store in Florida) and this is one of the better malt liquors Ive tried.

Bottle, purchased at the same place I found the Hurlimann Hexenbrau so it probably has a couple years age on it. Opaque black, abundant and dense tan head. Aroma very similar to a good port. Very full body. Quite wine-like, although with some Starbucks-evoking roast and very subtle yet pleasant hops. It should be served close to room temperature; when fresh out of the fridge its somewhat unnervingly metallic. This does pass quickly, though. All in all an extremely good beer.

Purchased this afternoon for one dollar at a little second-hand store, found on a shelf mainly inhabited by empty bottles of long-dead American regionals. Practically opaque brown beer, dense light tan head. Aroma of malt and caramel. Flavor extremely malty, caramel, some roast and hints of dried fruit. Very faint hop grassiness. Medium to full body. Very drinkable, although I really should savor it slowly since its been discontinued. Quite good.

I cant find a date on the bottle, the neck label must have fallen off. This was the last one at the Six Pack Shop in Fountain Hill... Opaque cola colored beer, scant head. I get a lot of interesting complex dried fruit, chocolate, coffee, caramel, vinous-ness and other excellent barleywine notes, but for some reason these are hidden under an aroma and flavor distressingly reminiscent of burning plastic. As it warms, the burning plastic begins to resolve into kind of a smoke/horseblanket/sourness/sherry kind of thing, which is actually rather nice so I am going to abandon my earlier plans to give this an extremely low rating.
